  "prompt": "Which library is better than the BGI library(graphics.h) for graphics in C++?",
  "response": "The BGI library, which is part of the old Borland graphics interface, is quite outdated and not widely used for modern C++ programming. There are many more powerful and flexible libraries available for graphics in C++. Here are a few of them:\n\n### SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer)\nSDL is a widely-used library for handling graphics as well as input, sound, and networking. It's suitable for game development and other applications that require high performance. SDL supports 2D graphics and can be used in conjunction with OpenGL for 3D graphics.\n\n- Website: [SDL](https://www.libsdl.org/)\n- Documentation: [SDL Documentation](https://wiki.libsdl.org/FrontPage)\n\n### SFML (Simple and Fast Multimedia Library)\nSFML provides a simple interface for creating windows, handling input, drawing 2D graphics, and more. It's designed to be user-friendly and is great for beginners who want to create graphical applications quickly.\n\n- Website: [SFML](https://www.sfml-dev.org/)\n- Documentation: [SFML Documentation](https://www.sfml-dev.org/documentation.php)\n\n### OpenGL\nOpenGL is a powerful and widely-used graphics API that is more complex than SDL and SFML. It's suitable for applications that require high-performance 3D graphics. OpenGL provides fine-grained control over the graphics pipeline, but it has a steeper learning curve.\n\n- Website: [OpenGL](https://www.opengl.org/)\n- Documentation: [OpenGL Documentation](https://www.opengl.org/documentation/)\n\n### Qt\nQt is a complete application development framework that includes powerful tools for creating graphical user interfaces. It also supports OpenGL for integrating 3D graphics. Qt is suitable for developing both desktop and embedded applications.\n\n- Website: [Qt](https://www.qt.io/)\n- Documentation: [Qt Documentation](https://doc.qt.io/)\n\n### Allegro\nAllegro is a cross-platform library mainly used for game programming. It handles graphics, input, sound, and more. It's user-friendly and somewhat similar to SDL in scope.\n\n- Website: [Allegro](https://liballeg.org/)\n- Documentation: [Allegro Documentation](https://liballeg.org/docs.html)\n\n### Vulkan\nVulkan is a newer graphics API developed by the Khronos Group, providing high-efficiency, cross-platform access to modern GPUs. Vulkan offers more control over the GPU and lower-level access compared to OpenGL, but this comes at the cost of increased complexity.\n\n- Website: [Vulkan](https://www.khronos.org/vulkan/)\n- Documentation: [Vulkan Documentation](https://www.khronos.org/vulkan/)\n\n### Comparison\nChoosing the right library depends on your specific needs and expertise level. If you need something simple and easy for beginners, SFML and SDL are good options. For more advanced 3D graphics, OpenGL and Vulkan are suitable choices. For comprehensive application development with GUI and graphics, Qt is highly recommended.\n\nEach library has its own advantages and use-cases, so consider your project requirements and development goals when making your choice.",
